lete assimilation nor unyielding separatism. Instead, the development of a distinctive regional identity will be based on Latino definitions of what it means to be American. This updated edition now provides trend lines through the 2010 Census as well as information on the 1849 California Constitutional Convention and the ethnogenesis of how Latinos created the society of ";Latinos de Estados Unidos"; (Latinos in the US). In addition, two new chapters focus on Latino Post-Millennials—the first focusing on what it’s like to grow up in a digital world; and the second describing the contestation of Latinos at a national level and the dynamics that transnational relationships have on Latino Post-Millennials in Mexico and Central America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aHispanic AmericanszCaliforniavStatistics. 0aHispanic AmericanszCaliforniaxEthnic identity. 0aHispanic AmericanszCaliforniaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh  aamerica.  aamerican birth rate.  aamerican identity.  aanalysis.  aassimilation.  ababies.  abirth rate.  abirth.  abusiness owner.  acalifornia.  acensus.  acentral america.  aculture.  adigital native.  adigital world.  adomestic.  afamily life.  agolden state.  ahealth and wellness.  aimmigrant.  aimmigration.  alatino culture.  alatino.  alatinx culture.  alatinx.  alife expectancy.  amexico.  apost millennials.  aregional identity.  aregional.  aseparatism.  aunited states.  aus birth rate.  awork ethic.  awork.  aworkplace.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052029252940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520966024423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docum